{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515207"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:30:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:30:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12419"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12419"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.04,0.05,0.8,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110724"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4927"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92975"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2232"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8057"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44826"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110724"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old man presents with a steadily worsening one week history of fever, cough and difficulty breathing. His medical history is significant for a positive HIV test for which he is on raltegravir+emtricitabine but he reports not taking them regularly. On examination his blood pressure is 110/72 mmHg, pulse 110/min, temperature 38.8\u00b0C and respiratory rate 24/min. Widespread crackles are heard on chest auscultation. Investigations reveal a WBC count of 15 x10\u003Csup\u003E^\u003C/sup\u003E9/L (4-11), CD4 count 159 cell/mm^3 (500 to 1500). A chest X-ray shows diffuse infiltration in both lung fields. GeneXpert MTB is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Cryptococcus neoformans","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Pneumocystis jirovecii","Cryptosporidium parvum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of the patient is consistent with pneumonia. Although \u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E is the commonest infecting organisms in most immunocompromised (including HIV) patients, \u003Cstrong\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most common organism predominantly causing pneumonia in patients with CD4 count less than 200 cells/mm3, making it the most likely cause in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryptococcus neoformans\u003C/strong\u003E typically grows as a yeast (unicellular) and replicates by budding and is known to cause meningitis in patients with AIDS. This organism undergoes reproduction forming dikaryotic hyphae and basidiospores supported by a club-shaped basidium with hyphae that has a complex septate appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryptosporidium parvum\u003C/strong\u003E is one of several species that cause cryptosporidiosis, a parasitic disease of the intestinal tract commonly causing diarrhoea in patients with AIDS. Infection is caused by ingestion of sporulated oocysts transmitted by the faecal-oral route.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae i\u003C/strong\u003Es a Gram-negative, non-motile, encapsulated, facultative anaerobic, rod-shaped bacterium usually causing pneumonia in alcoholics, diabetics and not commonly in AIDS patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EXpert MTB/RIF\u003C/strong\u003E test provides fast and accurate detection of Mycobacterium Tuberculosis (MTB) and Rifampicin (RIF) resistance simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pneumocystis jirovecii is the most common organism causing pneumonia in a patient with CD4 count \u003C200 cells/mm3 in AIDS.","Diffuse bilateral infiltrates on chest X-ray in an HIV-positive patient with low CD4 count suggest Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia."],"references":["N\u00fcesch R, Bellini C, Zimmerli W. Pneumocystis carinii pneumonia in human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)-positive and HIV-negative immunocompromised patients. Clin Infect Dis. 1999 Dec;29(6):1519-23. doi: 10.1086/313534. PMID: 10585806. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10585806/","Siegel M, Masur H, Kovacs J. Pneumocystis jirovecii Pneumonia in Human Immunodeficiency Virus Infection. Semin Respir Crit Care Med. 2016 Apr;37(2):243-56. doi: 10.1055/s-0036-1579556. Epub 2016 Mar 14. PMID: 26974301. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26974301/","Truong J, Ashurst JV. Pneumocystis jirovecii Pneumonia. 2023 Jan 21. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29493992. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29493992/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92975"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12419"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92975"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-03T19:25:06+0